Mermaid Import & Export
TestCompass supports Mermaid‑based import and export to make models easy to share, version, and review across teams. Mermaid is a text‑based notation that integrates naturally with Markdown, Git, and documentation workflows, enabling transparent and traceable collaboration.
Purpose
Mermaid import and export allow teams to:
maintain models in Git with readable diffs
include models directly in documentation and technical discussions
reconstruct TestCompass models from existing Mermaid diagrams
keep behaviour descriptions consistent across documentation, development, and testing
The feature is designed for interoperability. The TestCompass model remains the authoritative representation for test generation and semantic validation.
Import
TestCompass can import Mermaid diagrams and convert them into a structured eMBT model.
During import, TestCompass:
interprets nodes and transitions according to eMBT semantics
validates the structure and highlights inconsistencies
preserves incomplete or ambiguous behaviour
prevents hidden logic or implicit branches from being introduced
Unsupported Mermaid constructs (for example, diagram types outside the TestCompass scope) are reported clearly so the user can adjust the source diagram.
Export
Any TestCompass model can be exported as a Mermaid diagram.
The exported Mermaid:
reflects the exact semantics of the underlying eMBT model
is stable, deterministic, and suitable for version control
can be embedded in Markdown, wikis, design documents, and code repositories
provides a documentation‑friendly view without altering the model itself
Exported diagrams are intended for communication and traceability. They are not a substitute for the TestCompass model used for test generation and impact analysis.
Workflow Integration
Mermaid import and export support common engineering workflows:
Git versioning: text‑based diffs reveal structural changes
Code reviews: reviewers can inspect model changes without opening TestCompass
Documentation: models can be embedded directly in README files, wikis, and design specs
Round‑tripping: teams can iterate between Mermaid diagrams and TestCompass models when needed
This ensures that modelling, documentation, and development remain aligned throughout the lifecycle.
